  "key_findings": [
    "dim(S_2^new(Gamma_0(N))) grows as ~0.047*N, roughly N/24 not N/12, because new subspace is about half the full space on average",
    "Prime levels sit almost exactly on N/12 (mean normalized residual = -0.028), confirming dim_new(p) ~ (p-1)/12",
    "Each additional prime factor of N reduces the new dimension by ~20-25% relative to N/12 (omega=2: -38%, omega=3: -62%, omega=4: -75%)",
    "Squarefree vs non-squarefree is a strong discriminator: squarefree levels have 2.2x the normalized dimension of non-squarefree",
    "omega(N) is the strongest predictor of dimension deficit: r=-0.72 correlation with normalized residual",
    "Prime concentration index: primes hold 22% of total dimension but are only 13.3% of levels (enrichment 1.65x)",
    "Most under-represented levels are highly composite numbers (e.g., 180, 396, 1260) -- lots of old forms crowd out new ones",
    "All top-20 over-represented levels are prime (ratio > 1.0, approaching the genus formula exactly)"
  ]
